        "content": "<p>A famous theorem by Lambek asserts that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> is an endofunctor of a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, and if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ξ</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>G</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\xi : X\\to GX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04601em;\">ξ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is its terminal coalgebra, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ξ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\xi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04601em;\">ξ</span></span></span></span> is an isomorphism.</p>\n<p>Until today, I stupidly believed that this was an if and only if! \"By the universal property of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ξ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\xi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04601em;\">ξ</span></span></span></span>, any other coalgebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,\\alpha)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> is an isomorphism, is the terminal coalgebra.\" However, it takes just the time to draw the right diagram to understand that this is false.</p>\n<p>So, I have two questions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What are the endofunctors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> for which it is true that if a coalgebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,\\alpha)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> has <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> invertible, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,\\alpha)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is terminal? I expect there are very few.</li>\n<li>Given G, is there a way to \"count\" how many <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>-coalgebras <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(A,\\alpha)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> invertible? I expect there are probably \"as much as the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">GX</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is big\", where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is the carrier of the terminal coalgebra.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Feel free to assume whatever you want on G and on its domain!</p>",
        "id": 224898033,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1612284104
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not quite answering your question, but are you aware of work by Stefan Milius and colleagues about characterising various kinds of coalgebras with invertible <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 224905803,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom Hirschowitz",
        "timestamp": 1612286862
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>However, it takes just the time to draw the right diagram to understand that this is false.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Even more simply, this applies to both terminal coalgebras and initial algebras, so, unless they coincide, this is immediately seen to be false.</p>",
        "id": 224906820,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1612287252
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You beat me to it by 30 seconds..... I thought I was going crazy thinking that Lambek's theorem also applies to initial algebras...</p>",
        "id": 224906899,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1612287292
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"grinning\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f600\" role=\"img\" title=\"grinning\">:grinning:</span> I left vague the concept of \"the right diagram\" on purpose</p>",
        "id": 224906975,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1612287313
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"383799\">Tom Hirschowitz</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/A.20converse.20to.20Lambek.20theorem/near/224905803\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Not quite answering your question, but are you aware of work by Stefan Milius and colleagues about characterising various kinds of coalgebras with invertible <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>No! My question is also meant to get acquainted with more literature on the subject</p>",
        "id": 224907067,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1612287357
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>IIRC, one of their contributions was to characterise a kind of \"regular\" fixed point. In lots of examples, the initial algebra intuitively consists of finite trees, while the final coalgebra consists of all, potentially wildly infinite trees. And their regular fixed point would catch something like regular trees, in the sense of finite trees with  \"loops\".</p>",
        "id": 224941653,
        "sender_full_name": "Tom Hirschowitz",
        "timestamp": 1612302377
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The only thing I remember which seems remotely relevant are \"algebraically compact functors\" where the initial algebra is isomorphic to the terminal algebra. There's some stuff by Barr <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002240499290169G\">here</a>.</p>",
        "id": 224963827,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1612316858
    }
]